<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  
    <base href="https://example.com/">
    <title>Example using <span> and <base>;</title>
    <style>
        
        .blue-text {
            color: blue;
        }
        .bold-text {
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Using <code><span></code> and <code><base></code> in HTML</h1>

    <p>This is a simple example demonstrating the usage of <code><span></code> and <code><base></code>.</p>

    <p>
        Here is a <span class="blue-text">span element</span> that changes the color of its text.
    </p>

    <p>
        This paragraph uses a <span class="bold-text">bold span</span> to emphasize part of its text.
    </p>

    <p>
        You can also use the <span style="background-color: yellow;">background color</span> property with <code><span></code>.
    </p>

    <p>
        The <code>"base"</code> element is used in the <code>"head"</code> section to specify the base URL for all relative URLs in the document. For example, if an image is referenced with <code>"img src="images/example-image.jpg"</code> and the <code><base></code> element is set to <code>https://example.com/</code>, the actual URL used will be <code>https://example.com/images/example-image.jpg</code>.
    </p>

    <p>
        <img src="images/example-image.jpg" alt="Example Image">
    </p>
</body>
</html>
